Understanding nearest neighbor classification

Introduction

  • nearest neighbor classifiers are defined by their characteristic of classifying unlabeled examples by assigning them to the class of similar labeled examples

  • With nearest neighbor classification, computers apply a human-like ability

    • recall past experiences to make conclusions about current circumstances

  • This strategy have been used successfully for:

    • Computer vision applications: optical character recognition and facial recognition in still images and video
    • Recommendation systems: predict whether a person will enjoy a movie or song
    • Identifying patterns: detect specific proteins or diseases in genetic data
    • Anomaly detection: identify unusual patterns in data

  • nearest neighbor classifiers are well suited for classification tasks where

    • relationships among the features and the target classes are numerous, complicated (or simply extremely difficult to understand)
    • yet the items of similar class types tend to be fairly homogeneous

The k-NN algorithm

  • The most prominent case is the k-nearest neighbors algorithm (k-NN)

  • it uses information about a caseâs k nearest neighbors to classify âunlabeledâ cases

  • The general steps in its implementation are:

    1. choose \(k\)
    2. the algorithm requires a training dataset made up of samples that have been classified into several categories
      • often labeled by a nominal variable
    3. for each âunlabeledâ record in the test dataset, k-NN identifies the \(k\) records in the training data that are the ânearestâ in similarity
    4. The âunlabeledâ test instance is assigned the class representing the majority of the \(k\) nearest neighbors

An age-old question

  • Is a tomato a fruit or a vegetable?

Measuring similarity with distance

  • Locating the tomatoâs nearest neighbors requires a distance function
    • a formula that measures the similarity between two instances
  • There are many ways to calculate distance
    • Euclidean distance
    • Manhattan distance
    • â¦
Distance to the tomato
Ingredient Sweetness Crunchiness Food Type Distance to the tomato
Grape 8 5 Fruit \(\sqrt{((6 - 8)^2 + (4 - 5)^2)} = 2.2\)
Green bean 3 7 Vegetable \(\sqrt{((6 - 3)^2 + (4 - 7)^2)} = 4.2\)
Nuts 3 6 Protein \(\sqrt{((6 - 3)^2 + (4 - 6)^2)} = 3.6\)
Orange 7 3 Fruit \(\sqrt{((6 - 7)^2 + (4 - 3)^2)} = 1.4\)

  • if using 1-NN, a tomato will be classified as a fruit

  • how about using 3-NN?

Choosing an appropriate k

  • The decision of how many neighbors to use for k-NN determines how well the model will generalize to future data

  • This is a classical bias-variance tradeoff problem

    • The balance between overfitting and underfitting the training data

  • A larger k has higher bias and lower variance than a smaller \(k\)

  • In practice, the choice of \(k\) depends on the difficulty of the concept to be learned and the number of records in the training data

  • One commonly suggested approach is to begin with \(k\) equal to the square root of the number of training examples

    • caution: such rules may not always result in the single best \(k\)

  • Choosing a large k reduces the impact of variance caused by noisy data but can bias the learner such that it runs the risk of ignoring small but important patterns

  • With every training instance represented in the final vote, the most common class always has a majority of the voters

    • The model would consequently always predict the majority class, regardless of the nearest neighbors

  • using a single nearest neighbor allows noisy data and outliers to unduly influence the classification of examples

    • For example, suppose some of the training examples were accidentally mislabeled

Preparing data for use with k-NN

  • Features are typically transformed to a standard range prior to applying the k-NN algorithm

  • the distance formula is highly dependent on how features are measured

  • rescale the features by shrinking or expanding their range such that each one contributes relatively equally to the distance formula

  • There are several common ways to do the rescaling

    1. min-max normalization \[X_{new}=\frac{X-min(X)}{max(X)-min(X)}\]

    2. z-score standardization \[X_{new}=\frac{X-\mu}{\sigma}\]

  • if certain features have a much larger range of values than others, the distance measurements will be strongly dominated by the features with larger ranges

Preparing data for use with k-NN

  • Notice that the Euclidean distance formula is undefined for nominal features

  • use dummy coding instead

\[male=\begin{cases} 1 & \text{if} \text{ x=male} \\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \]

  • An \(n\)-category nominal feature can be dummy coded by creating binary indicator variables for \(n - 1\) levels of the feature

  • one-hot encoding creates binary features for all n levels of the feature

  • uses dummy coding here even though you may encounter one-hot encoding sometime later

  • Nominal features and missing data require additional processing

  • For example, dummy coding for a three-category temperature variable

    • for example, hot, medium, or cold) could be set up as (3 - 1) = 2 features
    • one for hot and one for cold
    • medium is represented by the absence of both hot and cold

  • one-hot encoding creates binary features for all n levels of the feature, rather than n - 1 as with dummy coding

    • It is known as âone-hotâ because only one attribute is coded as 1 and the others are set to 0

  • virtually no difference between these two methods, and the results of machine learning will be unaffected by the choice of coding method

  • one-hot encoding has become prevalent in the field of machine learning and is often treated synonymously with dummy coding

  • the distance between dummy-coded features is always one or zero

    • the values fall on the same scale as min-max normalized numeric data
    • No additional transformation is necessary

  • For instance, cold, warm, and hot could be numbered as 1, 2, and 3, which normalizes to 0, 0.5, and 1

    • A caveat to this approach is that it should only be used if the steps between categories are equivalent

  • For instance, although income categories for poor, middle class, and wealthy are ordered,

    • the difference between poor and middle class may be different than the difference between middle class and wealthy

  • Since the steps between groups are not equal, dummy coding is a safer approach

What makes the k-NN algorithm distinctive

  • Classification algorithms based on nearest neighbor methods are considered lazy learning algorithms

    • no abstraction occurs
    • the abstraction and generalization processes are skipped altogether

  • Due to the heavy reliance on the training instances rather than an abstract model

    • lazy learning is also known as instance-based learning or rote learning

  • the heavy reliance on the training instances (rather than an abstract model) - instance-based learning

  • the method is said to be in a class of non-parametric learning methods

    • no parameters are learned about the data

  • Without generating theories about the underlying data, non-parametric methods limit our ability to understand how the classifier is using the data, yet it can still make useful predictions

  • Non-parametric learning allows the learner to find natural patterns rather than trying to fit the data into a preconceived and potentially biased functional form

  • This allows the training phase, which is not actually training anything, to occur very rapidly

  • the downside is that the process of making predictions tends to be relatively slow by comparison

  • The k-NN algorithm is also known as a memory-based algorithm because it stores all of the training instances and uses them to make predictions

  • The algorithm is said to be in a class of non-parametric learning methodsâno parameters are learned about the data

  • Without generating theories about the underlying data, non-parametric methods limit our ability to understand how the classifier is using the data, yet it can still make useful predictions

  • Non-parametric learning allows the learner to find natural patterns rather than trying to fit the data into a preconceived and potentially biased functional form

The strengths and weaknesses of k-NN

  • Strengths
    • Simple and effective
    • Makes no assumptions about the underlying data distribution
    • Fast training phase
  • Weaknesses
    • Does not produce a model, limiting the ability to understand how the features are related to the class
    • Requires selection of an appropriate \(k\)
    • Slow classification phase
      • Nominal features and missing data require additional processing
  • The KNN learning model is the entire training dataset
    • there is no learning required, just memorization
    • Instead of learning weights or parameters, each \(x_i\) is loaded into memory
    • KNN is a simple example of a non-parametric model where the model structure is determined from the dataset with no assumptions about the underlying data distribution
  • KNN does not work well in high dimensions unless data lie on or close to a low-dimensional subspace (manifold)
  • The KNN learning model simply returns the majority class of the \(k\) nearest \(x_i\) in the dataset \(D\):

\[ h(x)=sign(\frac{1}{k}\sum_{x_i \in N_k(x)} y_i) \]

  • \(N_k(xâ)\) consists of the \(k\) closest points to reference point \(x^â\) in the training data (\(k\)-nearest neighborhood)

Logistic regression as an alternative

  • let us recap some notations to formalize the discussion

  • Let \(X\) be a \(p\)-dimensional random vector representing the features

  • Let \(\mathcal{C}\) be a set of \(q\) classes

  • Let \(Y\) be a categorical response variable taking values in the set \(\mathcal{C}\)

  • the classification task is to build a function \(C(X)\)

    • takes \(X\) as input and predicts its value for \(Y\) i.e.Â \(Y=C(X) \in \mathcal{C}\)

  • The goal of logistic regression is to estimate the conditional probability

\[ P(Y = c|X = x) \quad \text{for each class } c \in\mathcal{C} \]

\(\quad\) where \(|\mathcal{C}|=2\)

  • why not using linear regression?
    • the response variable \(Y\) is categorical
    • the linear regression model may predict values outside the range of 0 and 1
    • the linear regression model may predict values that are not probabilities

Logistic regression

  • The logistic regression model is a linear model for binary classification, say 0 or 1

  • The model is defined as

\[ P(Y=1|X=x)=\frac{e^{\beta_0+\beta_1X_1+\ldots+\beta_pX_p}}{1+e^{\beta_0+\beta_1X_1+\ldots+\beta_pX_p}} \]

  • we may write \(p(x)=P(Y=1|X=x)\) for simplicity

  • In social science research, researchers might write the model in the log-odds form

\[ \log\left(\frac{P(Y=1|X=x)}{1-P(Y=1|X=x)}\right)=\beta_0+\beta_1X_1+\ldots+\beta_pX_p \]

  • the log-odds is also known as the logit function (or logit transformation of \(p(x)\))

Logistic regression

  • The model is estimated by maximizing the likelihood function

  • The likelihood function is the probability of observing the data given the model parameters

\[ \begin{aligned} L(\beta_0,\beta_1,\ldots,\beta_p)&=P(Y=y_1,X=x_1) \cdot P(Y=y_2,X=x_2) \cdot \ldots \cdot P(Y=y_n,X=x_n)\\ &=\prod_{i: y_i=1}^{n}P(Y=1|X=x_i)\prod_{i: y_i=0}^{n}P(Y=0|X=x_i) \end{aligned} \]

  • The likelihood gives the probability of the observed zeros and ones in the data

  • the training is to search for \(\beta\)s that maximize the likelihood function

  • The log-likelihood function is the natural logarithm of the likelihood function

Logistic regression - loan default example

  • Suppose we have a dataset of loan applicants
  • The response variable is binary: 1 for default and 0 for non-default
  • The features include the applicantâs income, student status, and balance amount
  • The logistic regression model estimates the probability of default given the applicantâs features
  • The model could then be used to predict the probability of default for new applicants

        1 
0.5857694

  • \(BIC=-2\log(L)+k\log(n)\)

    • where \(L\) is the likelihood function
    • \(k\) is the number of parameters
    • \(n\) is the number of observations

  • The BIC is a penalized version of the log-likelihood function

  • \(AIC\) is another criterion for model selection

    • AIC=-2(L)+2k
    • AIC is less stringent than BIC

  • deviance is a measure of the goodness of fit of the model

    • it is the difference between the log-likelihood of the model and the log-likelihood of the saturated model
    • the saturated model is a model that perfectly fits the data

Logistic regression with more than two classes

  • The logistic regression model can be extended to handle more than two classes, say \(q>2\) classes

  • The multinomial logistic regression model estimates the conditional probability of each class given the features

  • The model is defined as:

\[ P(Y=c|X=x)=\frac{e^{\beta_{c0}+\beta_{c1}X_1+\ldots+\beta_{cp}X_p}}{\sum_{c=1}^{q}e^{\beta_{c0}+\beta_{c1}X_1+\ldots+\beta_{cp}X_p}} \]

\(\quad\) for \(c=1,2,\ldots,q\)

  • The model is estimated by maximizing the likelihood function

  • Multi-class logistic regression is refered to as multinomial regression

  • it can be implemented in R using glmnet package with family = âmultinomialâ

  • we will not cover the details here
